WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:13.840
Domenos. Level 1. Pollyanna. By Eleanor H. Porter.

00:13.840 --> 00:16.800
Chapter 1 Miss Polly. 

00:16.900 --> 00:22.620
Miss Polly Harrington came quickly into her kitchen that June morning. 

00:22.700 --> 00:28.720
Nancy, please stop your work for a minute and listen to me, she said. 

00:28.820 --> 00:31.220
Nancy stopped at once. 

00:31.320 --> 00:33.780
Miss Polly wasn't easy to please.

00:33.980 --> 00:38.300
Usually she wanted Nancy to work more quickly. 

00:38.400 --> 00:47.000
Nancy's father was dead, her mother was ill, and she had two younger sisters and a brother at home.

00:47.100 --> 00:52.700
So she came to work for Miss Harrington, one of the richest women in town. 

00:52.800 --> 01:01.340
But Miss Polly was always angry when she did things badly and never smiled when she did them right.

01:01.440 --> 01:08.200
Later today, said Miss Polly. You can make the little back attic ready for a visitor. 

01:08.300 --> 01:15.020
My niece Miss Pollyanna Whittier is coming to stay. She's 11 years old.

01:15.020 --> 01:22.900
Is a little girl coming here? That's nice. Cried Nancy. She thought of her two

01:22.940 --> 01:30.260
happy little sisters at home. Nice. Said Miss Polly coldly. I don't know about

01:30.260 --> 01:38.860
that. Nancy's face was suddenly hot and red, but she's your sister's child, Miss.

01:38.860 --> 01:47.060
Of course he want her here. Nancy, my silly sister married young, had children

01:47.060 --> 01:53.500
early and couldn't care for them. I don't want to care for this child, but I

01:53.500 --> 02:01.780
must. Now don't forget that attic. And with that she left the kitchen. Back in her

02:01.780 --> 02:08.060
room Miss Polly opened the letter from a far away town in the west and read it

02:08.060 --> 02:16.820
again. Miss Harrington, I have sad news for you. Your sister's

02:16.820 --> 02:25.660
husband John Whittier died two weeks ago. He leaves a girl 11 years old behind him.

02:25.660 --> 02:32.660
John was the minister in the church here and wasn't very rich. His child has

02:32.660 --> 02:40.580
nobody to care for her now. Only you, her family in the east. John spoke of this

02:40.660 --> 02:48.220
before he died. Can you take her? We can put Pollyanna on the train to come to you.

02:48.220 --> 02:56.300
When I get your answer and please say yes, I can write and tell you the day and time

02:56.300 --> 03:09.260
of the train. Jeremiah O White. Miss Polly sat with the letter in her hand and thought

03:09.300 --> 03:16.580
of her sister Jenny, the girl's mother. When Jenny was 20, a rich older man from the

03:16.580 --> 03:23.500
town wanted to marry her, but she wasn't interested in him or his money. She wanted

03:23.500 --> 03:29.540
to marry young John Whittier for love. Her parents weren't happy about it, but she

03:29.540 --> 03:36.460
didn't listen to them. She married, left home and went west with her new husband.

03:37.260 --> 03:44.740
Miss Polly remembered it well. She was only 15, the youngest at the time. Her parents

03:44.740 --> 03:51.740
wanted nothing more to do with Jenny. Of course, Jenny wrote for a time. Her letters told them

03:51.740 --> 03:58.780
about her different children, but they all died when they were very young. Only the last

03:58.780 --> 04:08.100
child lived. Jenny gave her the name Pollyanna after her two sisters, Polly and Anna. That

04:08.100 --> 04:14.620
was their last news from her. Some years later, a letter came for them from a small

04:14.620 --> 04:23.900
town in the west. It was from John Whittier and brought sad news. Jenny was dead. Miss

04:23.900 --> 04:31.620
Polly thought about the past 25 years. She was 40 years old. Her father, mother and

04:31.620 --> 04:38.780
sisters were all dead. The big family house and all her father's money were now in her

04:38.780 --> 04:45.540
name. Some people said to her, why don't you live with a friend? But she didn't want a

04:45.540 --> 04:54.180
friend in the house. She liked living quietly. And now, Miss Polly stood up. She was happy,

04:54.180 --> 05:02.420
of course, to do the right thing and to take the girl into her home. But Pollyanna, what a silly

05:02.420 --> 05:14.500
name. Later that morning, Nancy made the back attic ready. Why is she putting the child here

05:14.900 --> 05:19.940
when she has lots of nicer rooms in the house to give her? She thought.

05:22.260 --> 05:29.140
That afternoon, she went out into the garden to speak to old Tom. He worked for Miss Polly there.

05:30.340 --> 05:35.140
Mr. Tom, a little girl's coming to live here, she said.

05:36.100 --> 05:43.060
Not with Miss Polly. Left Tom? Yes, she told me earlier today.

05:43.780 --> 05:49.220
Answered Nancy. It's her niece. She's 11 years old.

05:50.260 --> 05:56.660
That's Miss Jenny's little girl then. The old man said. And now she's coming to stay.

05:57.300 --> 06:04.340
That's wonderful. She's going to sleep in the attic, said Nancy. For me,

06:05.380 --> 06:12.820
that's not right. Old Tom didn't look happy at this, but then he gave a big smile.

06:13.380 --> 06:18.500
Say, what's Miss Polly going to do with a child in the house? He said.

06:19.380 --> 06:26.180
More important. What's a child going to do with Miss Polly in the house? Answered Nancy.

06:26.900 --> 06:33.220
The old man laughed. You don't like Miss Polly? He said.

06:34.020 --> 06:37.140
Nobody does. Answered Nancy.

06:37.940 --> 06:41.460
Ah, but you didn't know her when she was in love.

06:42.660 --> 06:48.340
In love, cried Nancy. Nobody loved her back, of course.

06:48.900 --> 06:51.940
Oh, yes, they did, said old Tom.

06:52.740 --> 06:55.700
And the man's living here in the town today.

06:56.340 --> 07:00.740
Who is he? It's not right to tell you. He said.

07:01.540 --> 07:07.060
And he looked up at the house. He was a true friend to the Harrington family.

07:07.620 --> 07:14.180
You could see it in his old blue eyes. So Miss Polly had a lover.

07:15.140 --> 07:18.020
I can't believe it, said Nancy.

07:18.820 --> 07:25.620
Well, when she was younger, she was beautiful. And she can be again.

07:26.260 --> 07:30.580
Said old Tom. Beautiful. Miss Polly.

07:31.300 --> 07:37.780
Yes. She needs to wear hats with flowers on them, to have her hair different,

07:38.500 --> 07:43.940
and to wear nice dresses again. Miss Polly's not old, Nancy.

07:45.540 --> 07:52.740
Well, she's never happy, said Nancy. And one of these days I'm going to leave.

07:53.300 --> 07:54.980
Goodbye, Nancy.

07:55.860 --> 07:58.180
It's not easy for you. I know.

07:59.140 --> 08:00.180
Said old Tom.

08:00.740 --> 08:02.260
But don't leave.

08:03.220 --> 08:05.940
And with that, he went back to his work.

08:06.500 --> 08:09.620
Nancy. Called a cold voice from the house.

08:10.900 --> 08:11.700
Yes, Miss.

08:12.260 --> 08:15.540
Cried Nancy, and she ran in at once.

08:16.260 --> 08:20.900
Some days later, Miss Polly told Nancy.

08:20.900 --> 08:24.740
My niece is arriving by train tomorrow at four.

08:24.740 --> 08:27.940
You can go with Timothy in the buggy and meet her.

08:27.940 --> 08:33.140
The letter says, fair hair, red dress, and a summer hat.

08:33.140 --> 08:35.540
You can find her with that, I'm sure.

08:37.540 --> 08:42.340
The next afternoon, Nancy and Timothy, old Tom's son,

08:42.340 --> 08:44.100
went to meet the train.

08:44.580 --> 08:48.180
Is she a good, quiet child, do you think?

08:48.180 --> 08:49.380
Asked Nancy.

08:49.380 --> 08:50.420
Who knows?

08:51.220 --> 08:52.580
Smiled, Timothy.

08:52.580 --> 08:58.420
But a bad, noisy child isn't going to make things easy at the house for any of us.

08:58.420 --> 09:00.820
You can be sure of that.

09:00.820 --> 09:05.620
When the train arrived, a little girl with long, fair hair,

09:05.620 --> 09:08.900
a red dress, and a summer hat got off.

09:08.900 --> 09:11.060
It was Pollyanna.

09:11.380 --> 09:12.660
It was Pollyanna.

09:20.340 --> 09:23.060
Chapter two, the glad game.

09:24.660 --> 09:28.980
Soon Pollyanna was in the buggy between Timothy and Nancy,

09:29.540 --> 09:32.340
and they were on the road to Miss Polly's house.

09:33.060 --> 09:35.300
I didn't have a black dress to wear.

09:35.940 --> 09:37.460
Said Pollyanna.

09:37.460 --> 09:41.220
But it's easier to be glad in red than black, I guess.

09:42.100 --> 09:43.140
Glad.

09:43.140 --> 09:44.660
Cried Nancy.

09:44.660 --> 09:50.180
Yes, because now father's with mother and my dead brothers and sisters.

09:50.180 --> 09:52.180
Father said that before he died.

09:52.980 --> 09:54.900
And of course, I'm glad too.

09:55.620 --> 09:57.700
Because I have you, Aunt Polly.

09:58.660 --> 09:58.900
Me?

09:59.860 --> 10:01.460
But I'm Nancy.

10:02.260 --> 10:03.780
I work for Miss Polly.

10:04.580 --> 10:06.180
Oh, I see.

10:06.820 --> 10:08.100
Answered Pollyanna.

10:08.980 --> 10:11.620
So she didn't come to meet me?

10:12.580 --> 10:15.140
Well, I'm glad about that.

10:15.700 --> 10:20.020
Because now I have you, and I'm going to meet her soon too.

10:21.300 --> 10:24.820
Miss Polly was in the front room when they arrived.

10:24.820 --> 10:28.340
Hello Pollyanna, she said without a smile.

10:29.540 --> 10:33.300
Pollyanna ran and took the older woman in her arms.

10:33.940 --> 10:36.660
I'm very glad to meet you, Aunt Polly.

10:37.540 --> 10:39.860
Now, about my red dress.

10:40.820 --> 10:41.700
Father said...

10:41.700 --> 10:44.740
Let's not talk about your father, child.

10:44.740 --> 10:45.700
Your bag.

10:45.700 --> 10:47.060
There isn't much in it.

10:47.700 --> 10:49.060
Only father's books.

10:49.060 --> 10:53.060
And Pollyanna, I don't want to hear about your father.

10:53.060 --> 10:54.420
Do you understand?

10:54.420 --> 10:55.700
Yes, Aunt Polly.

10:56.340 --> 10:58.260
Said the girl sadly.

10:58.260 --> 10:59.780
Your bag's in your room.

11:00.340 --> 11:01.620
Aunt Polly finished.

11:02.100 --> 11:04.500
Timothy took it up, so come with me.

11:05.460 --> 11:08.340
Pollyanna went upstairs after her aunt.

11:09.060 --> 11:13.220
There were lots of beautiful pictures to left and right,

11:13.220 --> 11:17.380
wonderful rooms, and a nice green carpet under her feet.

11:18.420 --> 11:20.660
But when they went into her room,

11:20.660 --> 11:22.980
it had no pictures or carpet in it.

11:23.620 --> 11:29.060
Only a bed, a chair, a window, a table, and a closet.

11:29.940 --> 11:32.020
Here we are, said Miss Polly.

11:32.660 --> 11:35.140
Nancy can help you put your things away,

11:35.140 --> 11:36.420
suppers at six o'clock.

11:37.140 --> 11:39.700
And with that, she went downstairs.

11:41.140 --> 11:42.740
When Nancy came up,

11:42.740 --> 11:45.940
she found Pollyanna with her hands over her face.

11:46.740 --> 11:49.300
Sadly, the girl opened her bag,

11:49.300 --> 11:52.660
and Nancy took some old dresses and books from it,

11:52.660 --> 11:53.700
and put them away.

11:54.500 --> 11:57.860
At the same time, Pollyanna looked through the window.

11:58.660 --> 12:03.140
Oh, Nancy, I don't need pictures when I can see houses,

12:03.140 --> 12:06.100
trees, and the river through this, she said.

12:07.140 --> 12:10.020
Just then, they heard a bell downstairs.

12:11.540 --> 12:13.780
I must go now, said Nancy,

12:14.340 --> 12:16.580
and she went down to help with the supper.

12:17.460 --> 12:20.580
Pollyanna soon felt hot in her room,

12:20.580 --> 12:22.020
and she opened the window.

12:23.380 --> 12:27.060
Then, with a laugh, she climbed out through the window,

12:27.060 --> 12:30.260
down the tree in front of it, and into the garden.

12:31.140 --> 12:34.660
From there, she ran to a little hill not far away.

12:35.620 --> 12:38.740
Old Tom was in the garden, and he saw her go.

12:39.860 --> 12:41.700
Soon, she was up the hill,

12:41.700 --> 12:44.420
and she didn't hear the supper bell at six o'clock.

12:46.260 --> 12:50.900
My niece is late, said Miss Polly to Nancy at the supper table.

12:51.540 --> 12:53.860
She can have bread and milk in the kitchen.

12:54.820 --> 12:57.620
After supper, Nancy went upstairs,

12:57.620 --> 12:59.620
but Pollyanna wasn't in her room.

13:00.340 --> 13:02.500
So Nancy went out into the garden.

13:03.140 --> 13:05.220
Pollyanna's up the hill over there.

13:05.860 --> 13:06.980
Said old Tom,

13:07.540 --> 13:10.340
Nancy went at once and brought the girl in.

13:11.540 --> 13:12.740
How did you get out there?

13:13.300 --> 13:14.180
Nancy asked.

13:15.140 --> 13:16.340
Pollyanna told her.

13:17.700 --> 13:19.860
Well, you were late for supper,

13:20.660 --> 13:25.220
so you must have bread and milk with me in the kitchen tonight, your aunt says.

13:26.180 --> 13:30.020
Oh, I'm glad, smiled Pollyanna.

13:30.020 --> 13:34.740
I like bread and milk, and I'd like to have supper with you too.

13:36.100 --> 13:38.740
How can you be glad about everything?

13:39.620 --> 13:42.340
Well, it's the glad game, you know.

13:42.900 --> 13:44.180
My father taught it to me.

13:44.820 --> 13:48.500
You must always find the good in everything and be glad about it.

13:48.500 --> 13:49.780
It isn't always easy.

13:50.980 --> 13:53.860
Before bed, Miss Polly spoke to her niece.

13:54.420 --> 13:59.860
I'm sorry about supper tonight, Pollyanna, but you must learn to be on time.

14:00.820 --> 14:03.700
Oh, don't feel bad, Aunt Polly.

14:03.700 --> 14:05.220
Said Pollyanna.

14:05.220 --> 14:08.500
I was glad to have bread and milk in the kitchen with Nancy.

14:10.660 --> 14:14.660
The next afternoon, Miss Polly took Pollyanna into town.

14:15.220 --> 14:18.340
We must get you some new clothes, she said.

14:19.060 --> 14:20.260
New clothes?

14:20.260 --> 14:21.620
Cried Pollyanna.

14:21.620 --> 14:23.140
You're very good to me.

14:23.860 --> 14:27.620
I don't know about good, answered Miss Polly.

14:27.620 --> 14:31.860
With you and old clothes, people are going to think badly of me.

14:31.860 --> 14:33.380
I don't want that.

14:33.380 --> 14:36.260
Of course not, said Pollyanna.

14:36.260 --> 14:38.260
And you are good, Aunt Polly.

14:38.900 --> 14:40.980
But you don't feel glad about it.

14:41.700 --> 14:42.340
Why not?

14:43.140 --> 14:45.780
I'm always glad when I do something good.

14:46.420 --> 14:47.780
Be quiet, child.

14:48.420 --> 14:49.620
Said Miss Polly.

14:49.620 --> 14:51.460
Or we're going home this minute.

14:52.020 --> 14:54.420
Pollyanna stopped talking at once.

14:56.420 --> 15:00.500
That evening, it was very hot again in Pollyanna's room,

15:00.500 --> 15:01.780
and she couldn't sleep.

15:02.660 --> 15:06.260
So she got out of bed and went to the back attic room.

15:07.060 --> 15:12.820
She opened the window there and climbed out onto the roof of Miss Polly's room.

15:12.820 --> 15:15.060
I can sleep here, she thought.

15:15.780 --> 15:21.300
But Miss Polly heard noises in the night and called Timothy on the telephone.

15:21.300 --> 15:23.860
Come quickly, there's someone on my roof.

15:24.420 --> 15:25.140
She cried.

15:25.940 --> 15:30.820
When Timothy came, he found Pollyanna out on the roof and took her in.

15:31.540 --> 15:34.420
What were you doing on my roof, girl?

15:34.420 --> 15:36.180
Asked Miss Polly angrily.

15:36.980 --> 15:41.940
Oh, Aunt Polly, I wanted to sleep out under the night sky.

15:41.940 --> 15:43.700
Begin, Pollyanna.

15:43.700 --> 15:48.020
Well, now you must sleep in bed with me tonight, Pollyanna,

15:48.020 --> 15:51.060
because I don't want this to happen again.

15:51.060 --> 15:52.580
Oh, thank you.

15:52.580 --> 15:54.100
Cried Pollyanna.

15:54.100 --> 15:57.860
What a wonderful thing to sleep in my aunt's bed.

15:57.860 --> 15:59.380
Miss Polly couldn't speak.

16:00.260 --> 16:04.980
Why, when she wanted to punish her niece, was the girl always glad.

16:04.980 --> 16:14.260
Chapter 3. New Friends

16:16.020 --> 16:20.500
The weeks went by and Pollyanna felt happy in her new home.

16:21.380 --> 16:24.180
But it wasn't easy to talk to Miss Polly.

16:24.980 --> 16:29.780
Nancy was Pollyanna's only friend and she always had work to do.

16:30.820 --> 16:33.780
So Pollyanna wanted to go out and meet people.

16:34.980 --> 16:37.380
Mrs. Snow lived not far away.

16:38.260 --> 16:41.940
She was a very sick woman and never left her bed.

16:42.980 --> 16:48.900
Miss Polly usually sent Nancy to her house on Thursday afternoons with something for her to eat.

16:49.700 --> 16:51.700
Chicken, soup, or jelly.

16:52.500 --> 16:53.620
Can I go today?

16:54.100 --> 16:56.580
Pollyanna asked Nancy one Thursday.

16:57.700 --> 16:59.540
Mrs. Snow's never happy.

17:00.260 --> 17:01.060
Said Nancy.

17:01.620 --> 17:04.340
When she gets chicken, she wants soup.

17:05.060 --> 17:07.380
When it's soup, she wants jelly.

17:08.340 --> 17:09.620
You don't want to go.

17:10.500 --> 17:11.220
Yes, I do.

17:12.180 --> 17:15.700
So Pollyanna went to Mrs. Snow's house that afternoon.

17:16.740 --> 17:20.980
Miss Snow, a tired young woman, took the girl to her mother

17:21.540 --> 17:23.780
and left her there in the dark room.

17:24.420 --> 17:26.420
Here's some jelly from Aunt Polly.

17:26.980 --> 17:27.940
Said Pollyanna.

17:28.900 --> 17:30.740
I wanted soup today.

17:31.540 --> 17:33.380
Said Mrs. Snow from the bed.

17:33.860 --> 17:35.380
That's strange.

17:35.380 --> 17:36.580
Cried Pollyanna.

17:37.380 --> 17:42.660
Usually you want chicken when you get jelly and soup when it's chicken.

17:43.300 --> 17:44.260
Nancy told me.

17:45.460 --> 17:46.980
Mrs. Snow sat up.

17:47.620 --> 17:50.580
What a thing to say, she cried.

17:51.220 --> 17:52.500
Who are you?

17:53.380 --> 17:54.820
I'm Miss Polly's niece.

17:55.540 --> 17:58.980
I live with her now and I'm here with your jelly.

17:59.860 --> 18:01.620
I'm not hungry.

18:01.700 --> 18:05.220
I didn't sleep at all last night.

18:05.220 --> 18:06.260
Said Mrs. Snow.

18:07.220 --> 18:08.420
That's wonderful.

18:08.980 --> 18:10.020
Said Pollyanna.

18:10.820 --> 18:13.220
We lose lots of time when we sleep.

18:14.020 --> 18:16.260
I'd like not to sleep at night too.

18:17.220 --> 18:18.100
What's that?

18:19.220 --> 18:20.500
Open the curtains.

18:21.060 --> 18:22.740
I want to see you.

18:23.540 --> 18:24.500
Said Mrs. Snow.

18:25.780 --> 18:28.020
So Pollyanna opened the curtains.

18:28.740 --> 18:30.420
You're beautiful.

18:30.420 --> 18:33.940
Cried Pollyanna when she saw Mrs. Snow in the sun.

18:34.660 --> 18:37.060
I love your dark eyes and hair.

18:38.500 --> 18:41.860
That afternoon Pollyanna did Mrs. Snow's hair

18:42.500 --> 18:44.420
and put a pink flower in it.

18:45.780 --> 18:50.020
Miss Snow had a surprise when she came in after Pollyanna left.

18:51.300 --> 18:53.380
Mother, the curtains.

18:54.020 --> 18:54.740
She cried.

18:55.860 --> 18:57.460
I wanted them open.

18:58.100 --> 18:59.060
Said Mrs. Snow.

18:59.780 --> 19:03.380
And why do people bring me only things to eat?

19:04.020 --> 19:07.620
I'd like something nice to wear sometimes too.

19:10.020 --> 19:15.060
In September after a long summer Pollyanna started school.

19:15.940 --> 19:19.060
On her first morning she met a man in the street.

19:19.860 --> 19:26.100
He wore a tall black hat and a long black coat and he didn't smile.

19:27.060 --> 19:28.180
It's a nice day.

19:28.980 --> 19:30.020
Said Pollyanna.

19:30.580 --> 19:31.700
Are you talking to me?

19:32.340 --> 19:33.460
He said angrily.

19:34.260 --> 19:35.380
He didn't stop.

19:36.100 --> 19:39.940
The next day when Pollyanna saw him he had an umbrella.

19:40.740 --> 19:43.060
I don't like it when it rains.

19:43.060 --> 19:43.700
She said.

19:44.180 --> 19:46.580
But it doesn't rain every day.

19:46.580 --> 19:47.940
I'm glad about that.

19:48.820 --> 19:50.340
The man said nothing.

19:51.780 --> 19:52.660
Did he hear me?

19:53.300 --> 19:53.860
She thought.

19:54.500 --> 19:59.140
The day after when they next met the sun was in the sky.

20:00.020 --> 20:01.140
Pollyanna said.

20:02.020 --> 20:04.100
It's a nicer day than yesterday.

20:04.820 --> 20:05.620
Who are you?

20:06.260 --> 20:07.540
Said the man angrily.

20:08.020 --> 20:10.980
And why do you always tell me about the weather?

20:10.980 --> 20:13.460
I have more important things to think about.

20:14.260 --> 20:17.860
I'm telling you because you don't have time to look at the sky.

20:18.740 --> 20:20.180
I'm Pollyanna Whittier.

20:20.820 --> 20:21.460
Who are you?

20:22.180 --> 20:23.460
Why of all the.

20:23.460 --> 20:24.420
Began the man.

20:25.140 --> 20:26.340
Then he walked away.

20:27.460 --> 20:30.260
The next time Pollyanna met him he said.

20:31.460 --> 20:32.260
Good afternoon.

20:32.820 --> 20:35.300
And before you speak can I say something?

20:35.860 --> 20:38.100
It's a beautiful day and I know it.

20:38.740 --> 20:39.060
Yes.

20:39.700 --> 20:42.500
I saw it in your smile before you spoke.

20:42.500 --> 20:43.460
Said Pollyanna.

20:44.100 --> 20:44.580
Did you?

20:45.220 --> 20:46.100
Answered the man.

20:46.900 --> 20:52.660
Nancy had a surprise when she went for a walk with Pollyanna and the man said.

20:52.660 --> 20:53.460
Good afternoon.

20:53.460 --> 20:54.500
To them.

20:55.540 --> 20:57.300
He spoke to you.

20:57.300 --> 20:58.500
Nancy cried.

20:58.500 --> 20:59.300
Yes.

21:00.340 --> 21:01.300
He always does.

21:01.300 --> 21:01.700
Now.

21:01.700 --> 21:03.700
Answered Pollyanna.

21:04.500 --> 21:07.300
But that's John Pendleton.

21:07.300 --> 21:11.300
He lives alone in a house on Pendleton Hill.

21:11.300 --> 21:14.100
He never speaks to people.

21:14.100 --> 21:20.900
My friend Sally works at the hotel in town and he never talks when he eats there.

21:20.900 --> 21:24.900
He never eats expensively, of course.

21:24.900 --> 21:27.300
It isn't easy without money.

21:27.300 --> 21:28.900
Said Pollyanna.

21:28.900 --> 21:31.700
He's the richest man in town.

21:31.700 --> 21:33.700
Answered Nancy.

21:33.700 --> 21:36.900
But he doesn't like giving his money away.

21:36.900 --> 21:38.900
He's strange.

21:38.900 --> 21:42.900
Maybe he's strange when you don't know him.

21:42.900 --> 21:44.260
Don't know him.

21:44.260 --> 21:45.220
Said Pollyanna.

21:46.100 --> 21:47.380
But I like him.

21:48.580 --> 21:54.260
At about that time Pollyanna found a little cat in the street and took it home.

21:54.820 --> 21:58.180
After that she found a little dog and took that home too.

21:59.300 --> 22:05.140
Miss Polly didn't like animals but it wasn't easy to say no to Pollyanna.

22:06.020 --> 22:09.780
So fluffy the cat and Buffy the dog stayed.

22:10.740 --> 22:16.420
October came and one day Pollyanna met a boy in the street near her house.

22:17.140 --> 22:19.460
He was thin and in old clothes.

22:20.020 --> 22:20.660
Who are you?

22:21.220 --> 22:22.340
Asked Pollyanna.

22:22.900 --> 22:24.500
And what are you doing here?

22:25.460 --> 22:26.500
I'm Jimmy Bean.

22:27.220 --> 22:29.300
I left the orphans home this morning.

22:30.340 --> 22:33.380
I want to find a real home with real folks, see?

22:34.820 --> 22:38.500
It wasn't easy to lose your mother and father Pollyanna knew.

22:39.460 --> 22:41.060
So she took Jimmy home.

22:41.940 --> 22:44.980
And Polly can Jimmy Bean live with us?

22:44.980 --> 22:45.700
She asked.

22:46.660 --> 22:48.500
But Aunt Polly said no.

22:49.460 --> 22:51.540
And Jimmy left the house sadly.

22:52.660 --> 22:54.340
Pollyanna ran after him.

22:54.900 --> 22:55.620
Don't worry.

22:56.340 --> 22:58.580
I'm going to find you a real home.

22:58.580 --> 23:00.100
She told him in the street.

23:00.740 --> 23:02.180
Maybe the church can help.

23:02.740 --> 23:03.220
Let's see.

23:04.580 --> 23:07.540
So Jimmy went back to the orphans home that night.

23:08.180 --> 23:09.940
And Aunt Polly felt bad.

23:10.820 --> 23:12.900
The next day she told Nancy,

23:13.460 --> 23:17.860
please move Pollyanna's things down from the attic into the bedroom under it.

23:25.220 --> 23:28.340
Chapter four, things go wrong.

23:29.620 --> 23:33.140
When Nancy told Pollyanna about her new bedroom,

23:33.140 --> 23:35.540
she ran at once to her aunt.

23:35.540 --> 23:36.580
It's beautiful.

23:37.140 --> 23:38.260
She cried.

23:38.260 --> 23:40.740
With its pictures, carpet and curtains.

23:41.380 --> 23:42.980
Thank you Aunt Polly.

23:42.980 --> 23:44.100
I'm really glad.

23:44.660 --> 23:48.500
Pollyanna, please stop being glad about everything.

23:48.500 --> 23:49.860
I'm tired of it.

23:49.860 --> 23:51.620
You always say it.

23:51.620 --> 23:51.940
Why?

23:52.740 --> 23:54.020
It comes from our game.

23:54.740 --> 23:58.100
Father, Pollyanna began and then stopped.

23:58.900 --> 24:01.700
Aunt Polly didn't like to hear about her father.

24:02.420 --> 24:04.340
So she said nothing more about it.

24:05.220 --> 24:10.020
After dinner that day, Miss Polly phoned the minister's wife.

24:10.660 --> 24:15.460
I'm sorry, but I can't come to the charity meeting at the church this afternoon.

24:16.020 --> 24:17.460
I have a bad head.

24:18.900 --> 24:22.340
When Miss Polly went to her room, Pollyanna went out.

24:23.860 --> 24:25.140
Good afternoon ladies.

24:25.780 --> 24:27.140
I'm Pollyanna Whittier.

24:27.700 --> 24:30.260
She said when she went into the church meeting,

24:30.980 --> 24:32.580
did your aunt send you?

24:33.220 --> 24:35.220
Asked the minister's wife.

24:35.220 --> 24:37.700
No, it was my idea.

24:37.700 --> 24:39.060
Said Pollyanna.

24:39.060 --> 24:42.820
I want to help Jimmy Bean, a boy from the orphan's home.

24:43.700 --> 24:47.940
He's 10 years old and he wants real folks and a real home.

24:48.660 --> 24:51.060
Can one of you ladies take him into your house?

24:51.700 --> 24:56.100
The ladies talked a lot, but not one wanted to take Jimmy.

24:56.900 --> 25:00.340
In the end Pollyanna left the church sadly.

25:01.220 --> 25:05.460
She didn't go home but walked far into Pendleton Woods.

25:06.180 --> 25:09.620
There she found Mr. John Pendleton on the ground.

25:10.180 --> 25:11.460
What's the matter?

25:11.460 --> 25:12.180
She asked.

25:12.900 --> 25:15.860
I fell from those rocks up there and broke my leg.

25:16.660 --> 25:18.660
He said, I can't move.

25:20.420 --> 25:23.620
Then he took a key from his coat and gave it to her.

25:24.180 --> 25:26.180
Here's the key to my house.

25:26.180 --> 25:28.580
It's not far past those trees.

25:28.580 --> 25:31.780
Go there, open the front door and go in.

25:31.780 --> 25:35.140
By the door there's a telephone and a telephone book.

25:35.140 --> 25:38.980
Find Dr. Thomas Chilton's number and phone him.

25:38.980 --> 25:42.900
Tell him about my accident near Pendleton Hill Rocks.

25:42.900 --> 25:46.100
Then wait there for him to arrive and bring him here.

25:47.060 --> 25:50.340
Pollyanna went off with the key and was soon back.

25:51.060 --> 25:52.100
Did you get in?

25:52.180 --> 25:53.620
Mr. Pendleton asked.

25:54.260 --> 25:59.860
Yes and I phoned and Dr. Chilton's coming but I wanted to stay with you.

26:00.580 --> 26:04.020
When Dr. Chilton came he smiled at Pollyanna.

26:04.900 --> 26:06.980
Thank you young lady for your help.

26:07.940 --> 26:10.980
Then he looked carefully at Mr. Pendleton's leg.

26:13.540 --> 26:16.740
That evening Pollyanna arrived late for supper.

26:17.540 --> 26:18.980
Nancy met her at the door.

26:19.940 --> 26:21.300
Your aunt isn't here.

26:21.940 --> 26:25.060
She went to Boston suddenly to visit a sick friend.

26:25.700 --> 26:26.980
And I'm glad.

26:27.540 --> 26:29.780
Nancy cried Pollyanna.

26:30.420 --> 26:31.220
It's okay.

26:32.580 --> 26:35.060
I'm playing the glad game.

26:35.060 --> 26:36.180
Left Nancy.

26:36.980 --> 26:41.140
Then Pollyanna told Nancy about John Pendleton's accident

26:41.700 --> 26:44.020
and she listened with an open mouth.

26:44.820 --> 26:49.780
The next day Pollyanna told Jimmy Bean about the lady's charity meeting.

26:50.980 --> 26:51.780
I'm sorry.

26:52.500 --> 26:57.780
She said they were more interested in their charity work in India than in you.

26:58.580 --> 27:00.820
It's because India's far away I guess.

27:01.540 --> 27:03.220
Then she had an idea.

27:04.180 --> 27:04.740
I know.

27:05.620 --> 27:09.780
I can write to the ladies from my father's old church out west.

27:10.660 --> 27:14.020
Maybe they'd like to help you because you're far away.

27:14.980 --> 27:15.460
Okay.

27:16.340 --> 27:20.900
Said Jimmy and he went back to the orphan's home again that night.

27:22.100 --> 27:27.780
Three days later after her friend in Boston died Miss Polly came back home.

27:28.580 --> 27:32.340
Can I take Mrs. Snow's jelly to someone different today?

27:32.340 --> 27:34.260
Asked Pollyanna that Thursday.

27:34.900 --> 27:40.100
He broke his leg and he needs the jelly more than Mrs. Snow at the moment.

27:41.060 --> 27:45.940
And Pollyanna told her aunt all about John Pendleton's accident.

27:45.940 --> 27:49.140
John Pendleton cried Miss Polly.

27:49.140 --> 27:50.260
Do you know him?

27:50.900 --> 27:51.300
Yes.

27:51.860 --> 27:52.900
Said Pollyanna.

27:53.460 --> 27:55.540
So can I take him the jelly?

27:56.500 --> 28:01.140
Very well said her aunt but I didn't send you.

28:01.140 --> 28:03.460
You must be careful not to say that.

28:04.500 --> 28:08.260
Pollyanna found Dr. Chilton at John Pendleton's house.

28:09.780 --> 28:10.660
Come in.

28:10.660 --> 28:15.300
The doctor said and Pollyanna went into Mr. Pendleton's room.

28:16.180 --> 28:17.220
Why are you here?

28:17.940 --> 28:19.780
Cried the man in bed angrily.

28:20.420 --> 28:21.780
I brought you some jelly.

28:22.420 --> 28:23.460
Said Pollyanna.

28:24.020 --> 28:25.460
Nancy made it.

28:25.460 --> 28:26.900
She works for Aunt Polly.

28:27.540 --> 28:28.420
And Polly?

28:28.980 --> 28:30.740
Miss Polly Harrington.

28:30.740 --> 28:31.620
I live with her.

28:32.260 --> 28:33.380
With her?

28:33.860 --> 28:34.420
He said.

28:35.220 --> 28:37.700
His space was suddenly white.

28:37.700 --> 28:38.020
Yes.

28:38.580 --> 28:40.020
My mother was her sister.

28:40.660 --> 28:43.140
When father died they sent me to her.

28:44.180 --> 28:46.580
Did Miss Polly send that jelly for me?

28:47.300 --> 28:47.700
Oh no.

28:48.420 --> 28:50.740
I must be careful not to say that.

28:50.740 --> 28:51.940
She told me.

28:51.940 --> 28:52.580
I see.

28:53.380 --> 28:54.580
Said Mr. Pendleton.

28:55.220 --> 28:58.180
And he looked at Pollyanna very strangely.

28:58.340 --> 29:03.620
Dr. Chilton took her home in his buggy soon after that.

29:04.900 --> 29:08.820
A week after Pollyanna's visit to Mr. Pendleton's house,

29:08.820 --> 29:12.260
Miss Polly went to a lady's charity meeting at the church.

29:13.300 --> 29:18.900
When she came home her face was pink and her hair was dark from the rain.

29:19.780 --> 29:24.260
Why did you go to them about that orphan boy Pollyanna?

29:24.260 --> 29:25.860
She asked her niece.

29:25.860 --> 29:27.700
It was very bad of you.

29:28.500 --> 29:30.500
Pollyanna didn't listen.

29:30.500 --> 29:33.540
Your hair is beautiful today Aunt Polly.

29:33.540 --> 29:34.100
She said.

29:35.300 --> 29:38.820
She took her aunt up to her room, did her hair,

29:38.820 --> 29:40.580
and put a red flower in it.

29:41.380 --> 29:43.620
And Miss Polly couldn't stop her.

29:43.620 --> 29:44.580
Couldn't punish her.

29:45.300 --> 29:52.740
Then suddenly through the window they saw Dr. Chilton's buggy in the street with the doctor in it.

29:53.620 --> 29:56.980
Pollyanna opened the window and called out to him.

29:57.780 --> 30:00.020
Dr. Chilton, did you want me?

30:00.580 --> 30:01.300
I'm up here.

30:02.180 --> 30:04.820
Miss Polly ran from the window at once.

30:05.700 --> 30:07.140
What's the matter?

30:07.140 --> 30:08.740
Pollyanna called after her.

30:09.460 --> 30:10.980
Why did you do that?

30:11.620 --> 30:16.180
It's not right for folks to see me with a silly flower in my hair.

30:16.740 --> 30:17.620
Cried her aunt.

30:18.260 --> 30:19.700
What's the matter?

30:23.700 --> 30:24.660
Chapter 5.

30:25.380 --> 30:27.300
Someone very important.

30:28.580 --> 30:32.980
Pollyanna left her aunt upstairs and ran out to Dr. Chilton.

30:33.940 --> 30:34.900
What is it?

30:34.900 --> 30:35.540
She asked.

30:36.260 --> 30:38.260
Mr. Pendleton wants you.

30:38.260 --> 30:41.700
So after the rain stopped I drove over here.

30:41.700 --> 30:42.340
Can you come?

30:43.300 --> 30:44.740
I must ask my aunt.

30:45.300 --> 30:47.380
She came back nearly at once.

30:47.940 --> 30:48.260
Well?

30:48.820 --> 30:49.860
Asked the doctor.

30:50.660 --> 30:53.140
I can go, Pollyanna answered.

30:54.020 --> 30:57.060
But Aunt Polly spoke very strangely to me.

30:57.860 --> 31:00.100
She said, yes, go.

31:00.820 --> 31:02.340
Why didn't you leave before?

31:03.460 --> 31:07.220
Was your aunt upstairs at the window with you when I arrived?

31:07.220 --> 31:08.340
Asked the doctor.

31:09.140 --> 31:09.460
Yes.

31:10.180 --> 31:11.060
Did you see her?

31:11.700 --> 31:13.380
She was beautiful, I thought.

31:14.260 --> 31:15.220
What did you think?

31:15.860 --> 31:20.340
The doctor looked at Pollyanna, smiled sadly and said.

31:21.460 --> 31:21.780
Yes.

31:22.740 --> 31:25.620
For me she was beautiful too.

31:26.900 --> 31:29.380
Oh, I must tell her.

31:29.380 --> 31:31.540
Pollyanna, please don't.

31:32.420 --> 31:33.060
Why not?

31:33.780 --> 31:35.380
It's a nice thing to say.

31:36.340 --> 31:39.620
But maybe Miss Polly doesn't want to hear it from me.

31:40.580 --> 31:41.540
Maybe you're right.

31:42.420 --> 31:44.660
Dr. Warren's her doctor after all.

31:45.540 --> 31:48.340
And she ran from the window when she saw you here.

31:49.140 --> 31:52.420
And with that they went to Mr. Pendleton's house.

31:53.540 --> 31:56.420
Mr. Pendleton was very happy to see her.

31:57.220 --> 31:59.380
Do you have more jelly for me?

31:59.380 --> 32:00.820
Not from Aunt Polly?

32:00.820 --> 32:01.540
He laughed.

32:02.500 --> 32:04.980
Pollyanna's face was suddenly red.

32:05.620 --> 32:08.420
Did I say something wrong on my last visit?

32:08.420 --> 32:09.140
She asked.

32:10.020 --> 32:10.660
No.

32:10.660 --> 32:11.460
He answered.

32:12.020 --> 32:17.220
He had a box of beautiful old things from China and India by his bed that day.

32:17.940 --> 32:22.100
They opened it and took them out and Pollyanna played with them.

32:22.900 --> 32:24.900
And he and Pollyanna talked.

32:25.540 --> 32:32.020
They spoke of Nancy and Polly and Pollyanna's home with her father and mother out west.

32:33.220 --> 32:37.860
When it was time for her to go, John Pendleton said quietly.

32:37.860 --> 32:43.300
Pollyanna, when I learned about your folks last time, I didn't want to see you again.

32:44.020 --> 32:49.620
He reminded me of someone once very important for me from years ago and I felt sad.

32:50.340 --> 32:51.540
I wanted to forget you.

32:52.420 --> 32:53.940
But I can't do without you.

32:54.980 --> 32:58.340
I know that now, so please come and see me often.

32:58.980 --> 33:01.140
Of course, said Pollyanna.

33:01.140 --> 33:10.260
After supper, Pollyanna told Nancy about her visit.

33:11.060 --> 33:16.100
Lots of people don't like him, but he's very nice to me, she said.

33:16.740 --> 33:23.860
And it isn't always easy when I took him the jelly on my last visit and he heard about my folks.

33:24.580 --> 33:26.340
He didn't want to see me again.

33:27.380 --> 33:28.180
Why's that?

33:28.740 --> 33:29.860
Asked Nancy.

33:30.820 --> 33:37.860
And Pollyanna told Nancy about the someone very important for Mr. Pendleton from years ago.

33:38.980 --> 33:41.220
That's it, cried Nancy.

33:41.780 --> 33:43.300
Now I understand.

33:44.100 --> 33:44.900
What?

33:44.900 --> 33:46.180
Asked Pollyanna.

33:47.300 --> 33:55.300
Mr. John Pendleton and Miss Polly Harrington were lovers all those years ago.

33:55.380 --> 34:00.260
Cried Nancy, and she told Pollyanna about old Tom's story.

34:01.460 --> 34:08.980
But Mr. Pendleton doesn't like Aunt Polly, said Pollyanna, and she didn't want to send him the jelly.

34:09.780 --> 34:13.060
That's because they quarreled, said Nancy.

34:15.940 --> 34:23.460
On Pollyanna's next visit to John Pendleton's house, before she left, he again had a quiet talk with her.

34:24.260 --> 34:27.940
I feel very alone in this big old house, Pollyanna.

34:27.940 --> 34:33.380
I need a woman's hand and heart, or a child's face, near me to feel at home here.

34:34.020 --> 34:36.180
Would you like to come and live with me?

34:36.180 --> 34:37.460
Maybe I can adopt you.

34:38.260 --> 34:39.540
With Aunt Polly?

34:39.540 --> 34:41.060
Asked Pollyanna.

34:41.060 --> 34:42.100
Can she come too?

34:42.980 --> 34:43.860
Aunt Polly?

34:44.420 --> 34:47.140
Yes, because you loved her all those years ago.

34:47.860 --> 34:50.660
Well, no, not with Aunt Polly.

34:50.660 --> 34:52.260
He answered with a red face.

34:53.060 --> 34:56.340
And please, don't tell people about my plan for now.

34:56.340 --> 34:58.500
It's a secret. Do you understand?

35:00.020 --> 35:05.220
The next time Dr. Chilton took Pollyanna to Mr. Pendleton's house, she said,

35:06.020 --> 35:08.420
I'm going to tell you something, Dr. Chilton.

35:09.060 --> 35:11.620
It's a secret between Mr. Pendleton and me.

35:12.340 --> 35:14.420
But I can tell you, I think.

35:15.060 --> 35:16.740
It's only a secret from her.

35:17.940 --> 35:18.820
Her?

35:18.820 --> 35:20.020
As Dr. Chilton.

35:20.900 --> 35:21.700
And Polly.

35:22.340 --> 35:23.380
Said Pollyanna.

35:23.940 --> 35:30.020
And she told the doctor all about the old love between Mr. Pendleton and her aunt.

35:30.020 --> 35:32.820
And about Mr. Pendleton's plans to adopt her.

35:34.020 --> 35:34.340
Right.

35:35.140 --> 35:36.900
I didn't know about that.

35:37.460 --> 35:38.260
Said the doctor.

35:39.060 --> 35:41.380
And he was quiet for a long time.

35:42.100 --> 35:45.860
Maybe Mr. Pendleton wants to tell me more about it today.

35:45.860 --> 35:47.940
Said Pollyanna when they arrived.

35:48.900 --> 35:49.940
Maybe.

35:49.940 --> 35:51.620
Said Dr. Chilton.

35:51.620 --> 35:56.500
And he smiled strangely and drove off in his buggy back to town.

35:59.700 --> 36:04.180
On that visit, Mr. Pendleton explained everything.

36:04.180 --> 36:07.300
I didn't love Aunt Polly all those years ago.

36:07.300 --> 36:09.300
He told Pollyanna.

36:09.300 --> 36:13.060
I was in love with your mother before she married your father.

36:13.700 --> 36:15.220
But she didn't love me back.

36:16.100 --> 36:17.700
Oh, I see.

36:18.500 --> 36:19.620
Cried Pollyanna.

36:20.420 --> 36:23.060
When I met you, you reminded me of her.

36:23.620 --> 36:25.780
At first I didn't want to see you again.

36:26.500 --> 36:28.420
But now I want to adopt you.

36:29.140 --> 36:31.540
And what about Aunt Polly?

36:31.540 --> 36:33.460
No, I want only you.

36:34.340 --> 36:35.940
So can you ask her about it?

36:36.740 --> 36:37.220
All right.

36:38.660 --> 36:42.420
After her visit, Pollyanna walked back home.

36:42.500 --> 36:45.940
It began to rain after she left Pendleton Woods.

36:45.940 --> 36:49.220
But soon she met Nancy in the street with an umbrella.

36:50.260 --> 36:52.900
Miss Polly sent me to find you with this.

36:53.620 --> 36:54.500
Said Nancy.

36:55.460 --> 36:57.380
She was really worried about you.

36:58.180 --> 36:59.220
Was she?

36:59.220 --> 37:00.340
Asked Pollyanna.

37:01.060 --> 37:04.580
She couldn't leave her aunt and live with Mr. Pendleton now.

37:04.580 --> 37:05.460
She knew that.

37:06.260 --> 37:09.460
Aunt Polly was worried about her and needed her.

37:10.420 --> 37:14.260
But Mr. Pendleton really needed a child near him too.

37:14.260 --> 37:17.060
To make his big old house into a home.

37:18.180 --> 37:21.540
What could Pollyanna do to make the two of them happy?

37:24.420 --> 37:26.180
Suddenly she smiled.

37:26.980 --> 37:28.660
She had the answer.

37:28.660 --> 37:39.780
Chapter 6. The Gladest Things

37:41.620 --> 37:46.420
On Pollyanna's next visit to John Pendleton's house, he asked.

37:46.980 --> 37:48.420
Did you speak to your aunt?

37:49.060 --> 37:49.940
Can you live here?

37:50.980 --> 37:53.140
No, I can't.

37:53.140 --> 37:54.180
Did she say no?

37:55.140 --> 37:58.500
I didn't ask her, but she needs me.

37:59.300 --> 38:02.020
And I have a different child for you to adopt.

38:02.580 --> 38:04.260
To make your house into a home.

38:05.140 --> 38:06.740
I'm really glad for him.

38:07.380 --> 38:07.780
For who?

38:08.420 --> 38:09.220
Jimmy Bean.

38:09.780 --> 38:10.980
Cried Pollyanna.

38:11.620 --> 38:14.180
And she explained about the poor orphan.

38:15.380 --> 38:19.300
I had a letter from my church ladies out west last week.

38:19.300 --> 38:22.340
She finished and nobody wanted him there.

38:23.220 --> 38:24.500
He was sad about that.

38:25.460 --> 38:31.620
Pollyanna left with an invitation for Jimmy and her to visit Mr. Pendleton next Saturday.

38:32.980 --> 38:39.860
One Thursday afternoon, Mrs. Snow sent Pollyanna to Dr. Chilton's house for some medicine.

38:40.820 --> 38:44.020
I never saw your home before, she said.

38:44.900 --> 38:46.340
There are only rooms.

38:46.900 --> 38:48.180
He answered.

38:48.180 --> 38:49.460
Not really a home.

38:50.180 --> 38:54.740
Do you need the hand and heart of a woman, or the face of a child too?

38:55.780 --> 38:57.620
Mr. Pendleton wanted those.

38:58.340 --> 38:59.940
Said Pollyanna.

38:59.940 --> 39:04.340
Oh, and you remember when I told you about him and Aunt Polly.

39:05.540 --> 39:07.300
Did you tell any folks that story?

39:08.100 --> 39:08.340
No.

39:09.140 --> 39:13.780
Good, because Mr. Pendleton explained everything to me later.

39:14.740 --> 39:17.540
He loved my mother, not Aunt Polly.

39:18.420 --> 39:22.020
But now he's going to adopt Jimmy Bean.

39:22.020 --> 39:25.700
So maybe you can get the hand and heart of a woman,

39:25.700 --> 39:30.180
or the face of a child, to make your rooms into a home, Dr. Chilton.

39:31.060 --> 39:34.420
Some women don't give hand and heart very easily.

39:34.420 --> 39:36.580
He answered quickly and stood up.

39:37.620 --> 39:39.700
Here's that medicine for Mrs. Snow.

39:39.700 --> 39:40.260
He said.

39:41.140 --> 39:44.500
All of this, of course, was before the accident,

39:45.060 --> 39:47.300
and that changed everything.

39:48.180 --> 39:49.220
How did it happen?

39:50.180 --> 39:53.780
On the last day of October, Pollyanna left school.

39:54.660 --> 39:58.500
She didn't look to left and right when she walked across the road.

39:59.380 --> 40:04.420
Suddenly, a car hit her, and she fell to the ground unconscious.

40:05.620 --> 40:08.100
By five o'clock, she was back at home.

40:09.060 --> 40:11.300
But when would she open her eyes?

40:12.500 --> 40:18.020
Nancy sat by her bed, and Miss Polly telephoned her doctor at once.

40:18.980 --> 40:23.060
When Dr. Warren came, he looked at Pollyanna carefully.

40:23.620 --> 40:29.220
Well, she didn't break an arm or a leg, but she hit her head badly.

40:29.220 --> 40:30.500
He told Miss Polly.

40:31.060 --> 40:32.100
And I'm worried.

40:34.180 --> 40:37.620
Next morning, Pollyanna opened her eyes.

40:38.260 --> 40:39.060
Where am I?

40:39.700 --> 40:40.420
What happened?

40:41.380 --> 40:43.380
Why can't I move my legs?

40:43.380 --> 40:44.100
She cried.

40:45.380 --> 40:48.100
Miss Polly explained about the accident.

40:49.460 --> 40:52.100
And now you must sleep, she said.

40:54.580 --> 40:56.900
So Pollyanna slept for days,

40:57.540 --> 41:01.460
and many people from the town came and left flowers for her.

41:02.500 --> 41:07.220
When John Pendleton arrived soon after Pollyanna's accident,

41:07.220 --> 41:09.460
Nancy ran to tell Old Tom.

41:10.340 --> 41:11.700
Mr. Pendleton's here.

41:12.660 --> 41:13.620
You don't say?

41:14.260 --> 41:15.460
answered the old man.

41:16.740 --> 41:20.180
Was he really Miss Polly's lover from long ago?

41:20.980 --> 41:22.100
Asked Nancy.

41:23.060 --> 41:27.220
I believed that once, but now I'm not sure.

41:28.260 --> 41:29.300
Don't be silly.

41:29.940 --> 41:33.780
He loved Miss Jenny, but she loved that young minister.

41:34.740 --> 41:41.220
When they married and left, Miss Polly felt sorry for John Pendleton and was nice to him.

41:42.340 --> 41:47.860
Maybe he understood something different, but for her they were only good friends.

41:48.980 --> 41:53.940
Then, in the town, people began to talk of love between them.

41:55.140 --> 42:00.980
After that, Miss Polly and John Pendleton quarreled, and he stopped coming here.

42:01.940 --> 42:04.660
In the front room, Mr. Pendleton asked.

42:05.460 --> 42:06.580
How is Pollyanna?

42:07.780 --> 42:10.660
I don't know, said Miss Polly coldly.

42:12.420 --> 42:13.860
She can't move her legs,

42:14.500 --> 42:18.740
but she talks about when you broke your leg and were in bed for only weeks.

42:19.540 --> 42:24.740
She's glad because that's different from poor Mrs. Snow in bed for years.

42:25.700 --> 42:28.420
It's very sad, she doesn't understand.

42:29.060 --> 42:31.940
I wanted Pollyanna to live with me, you know.

42:31.940 --> 42:35.860
He said, with you, said Miss Polly.

42:36.500 --> 42:41.060
Yes, but she wanted to stay here because you needed her, she said.

42:42.020 --> 42:45.060
Suddenly, tears came to Miss Polly's eyes.

42:46.420 --> 42:50.740
After some weeks, Dr. Warren called a specialist from New York.

42:51.540 --> 42:54.660
Dr. Mead came and looked at Pollyanna.

42:55.380 --> 43:00.180
When he left, he spoke quietly to Miss Polly by Pollyanna's door.

43:01.380 --> 43:06.500
Fluffy the cat was in Pollyanna's room at the time, and she wanted to go out.

43:07.380 --> 43:13.460
Just then, she pushed the door open, so Pollyanna heard everything.

43:14.740 --> 43:17.380
Well, she's never going to walk again.

43:18.260 --> 43:21.300
Said Dr. Mead, poor Pollyanna.

43:22.020 --> 43:26.340
When she was well, she taught the glad game to Mr. Pendleton,

43:26.340 --> 43:30.100
Mrs. Snow, Nancy, and lots of people in town.

43:31.060 --> 43:33.780
But now, she could never leave her bed.

43:34.740 --> 43:38.180
It wasn't easy for her to find a thing to be glad about.

43:39.620 --> 43:44.420
Mr. John Pendleton called on Aunt Polly again when he heard the news.

43:45.380 --> 43:47.540
Please tell Pollyanna something from me.

43:48.100 --> 43:49.700
He said before he left.

43:50.260 --> 43:54.020
Jimmy Bean came to see me, and he's going to be my little boy.

43:54.580 --> 43:59.140
I'm going to adopt him. Tell her that. Maybe she can feel glad about it.

44:00.020 --> 44:04.340
Yes, Mr. Pendleton said Miss Polly in surprise.

44:05.620 --> 44:09.940
Pollyanna was, of course, very glad to hear the news.

44:10.900 --> 44:17.220
Back home, Mr. Pendleton, and his friend Dr. Chilton sat in the front room and talked.

44:18.340 --> 44:20.660
You remember your friend at the hospital, Tom?

44:21.700 --> 44:23.220
Who, the specialist?

44:23.780 --> 44:27.620
Yes, he helps lots of people to walk after accidents.

44:27.620 --> 44:31.220
Take Pollyanna to him. Maybe he can help her, too.

44:32.580 --> 44:37.060
I can't, John. I must have a look at her before I can call my friend.

44:37.700 --> 44:40.180
But Dr. Warren is Miss Polly's doctor.

44:40.740 --> 44:43.540
I can't visit without an invitation from him.

44:44.260 --> 44:47.620
And after Miss Polly and I quarreled fifteen years ago,

44:48.180 --> 44:51.300
when folks in town began to call the two of you lovers,

44:51.860 --> 44:54.580
she's never going to ask me. You know that.

44:55.460 --> 44:59.700
I'm never going to visit her house again without an invitation from her.

45:00.340 --> 45:03.300
And she's never going to change her heart and forgive me.

45:04.260 --> 45:07.380
Please, Tom, forget all that. Think of the girl.

45:08.180 --> 45:14.100
I'm sorry, John, but without an invitation from Miss Polly, I can't visit Pollyanna.

45:15.140 --> 45:20.340
Now all this time, the window in the room was open and near the window.

45:20.900 --> 45:25.380
Because it was Saturday morning, Jimmy Bean was at work in the garden.

45:26.100 --> 45:30.980
He heard everything and went at once to speak to Miss Polly.

45:31.860 --> 45:37.140
That afternoon, an invitation came for Dr. Chilton to visit Pollyanna.

45:37.860 --> 45:39.300
Did you ask for me?

45:39.940 --> 45:42.740
Dr. Chilton asked Miss Polly when he arrived.

45:43.540 --> 45:46.980
I... I did, said Miss Polly.

45:47.380 --> 45:49.860
Her face was suddenly very pink.

45:50.580 --> 45:57.060
She didn't see Tom Chilton smile happily behind her back when he went up to Pollyanna's room after her.

45:57.460 --> 46:01.460
When Dr. Chilton left, Miss Polly told Pollyanna,

46:01.860 --> 46:08.260
next week, you're going to a hospital. A friend of Dr. Chilton's is going to care for you there.

46:08.260 --> 46:11.060
Maybe he can help you. We're going to see.

46:12.260 --> 46:17.060
And thank you, Pollyanna, for bringing Dr. Chilton back to me.

46:17.060 --> 46:19.060
I'm very glad.

46:19.060 --> 46:25.860
Oh, and Polly, so you were his woman's hand and heart from long ago.

46:25.860 --> 46:29.460
And heart from long ago, cried Pollyanna happily.

46:30.980 --> 46:34.420
Some months later, a letter arrived from Pollyanna.

46:35.300 --> 46:39.220
Mrs. Polly Chilton read it to her husband at breakfast.

46:40.820 --> 46:43.060
Dear Aunt Polly and Uncle Tom,

46:44.100 --> 46:47.540
today I walked from my bed to the window.

46:48.340 --> 46:52.900
I couldn't believe it, at last, and starting to walk.

46:53.860 --> 46:56.660
The doctors watched and smiled when I did it,

46:57.460 --> 47:00.500
and the hospital workers had tears in their eyes.

47:01.460 --> 47:07.140
I didn't cry. I wanted to laugh and sing. I can walk.

47:08.340 --> 47:13.540
I arrived here nearly ten months ago, but I'm not worried by that.

47:14.500 --> 47:16.580
I was there at your wedding after all.

47:17.780 --> 47:22.020
It was a wonderful idea to have your wedding here by my bed, Aunt Polly.

47:22.900 --> 47:26.900
Thank you. You always think of the Gladest Things.

47:28.420 --> 47:30.420
Soon I can go home, they say.

47:31.620 --> 47:35.300
I like to walk there. I don't want to take a buggy,

47:35.300 --> 47:36.900
not when I can go on foot.

47:38.420 --> 47:42.020
Legs are important, but you don't know it when they're working.

47:43.140 --> 47:45.940
When I lost my legs, I learned that.

47:46.660 --> 47:48.420
And I'm very glad about it.

47:49.300 --> 47:51.540
I'm very glad about everything.

47:52.500 --> 47:55.300
Tomorrow, I'm going to walk some more.

47:56.180 --> 47:57.780
Maybe to the door this time.

47:58.980 --> 48:02.340
Lots of love to everyone, Pollyanna.

